Notebook[{
Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", ".", "B", ".", " ", "In"}], " ", "this", " ", "notebook", " ", 
  
  SubscriptBox["n", "\[DoubleVerticalBar]"], "is", " ", "called", " ", 
  SubscriptBox["n", "z"], " ", "and", " ", 
  SubscriptBox["n", "\[Perpendicular]"], " ", "is", " ", "called", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["n", "x"], "."}]}]], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.974992504563621*^9, 3.97499253364776*^9}, {
   3.974992690458828*^9, 3.974992754281549*^9}, 3.9750670836754503`*^9, 
   3.975343886817339*^9},ExpressionUUID->"80ae25cd-4735-4b71-9656-\
7d42eb576a6a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "N . B . The thing called conductivity, sigma, in this notebook is actually \
4\[Pi]i/\[Omega] \[Times] \[Sigma] .  i . e . the plasma part of the \
dielectric tensor, \[Epsilon] .  For example the dissipative part of the \
actual conductivity, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["\[Sigma]", 
     RowBox[{"H", " "}]], ","}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e6b66ca3-e7d4-4f66-821a-37f50295777a"],
 " appears in the anti-Hermitian part of \[Epsilon].  But in this notebook,\
\[LineSeparator] (sigma \[DoubleLongLeftRightArrow] 4 \[Pi]i/\[Omega] \
\[Times] \[Sigma]) the dissipative part is sigma anti-Hermitian, while the \
reactive part is sigma Hermitian."
}], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8759156755983667`*^9, 3.8759157283315477`*^9}, {
   3.8759157892239723`*^9, 3.8759158506252413`*^9}, {3.8759158849868107`*^9, 
   3.8759159260568933`*^9}, {3.875915964356182*^9, 3.8759159787500353`*^9}, {
   3.87591602821859*^9, 3.8759161696135893`*^9}, {3.875916204349657*^9, 
   3.875916346122182*^9}, {3.875916381226675*^9, 3.8759164052759123`*^9}, {
   3.875916442871254*^9, 3.8759165125341883`*^9}, {3.875916559833077*^9, 
   3.8759166654086027`*^9}, {3.875920145401786*^9, 3.875920224126281*^9}, 
   3.875920254611403*^9, {3.8759634746389503`*^9, 3.875963478200918*^9}, 
   3.876063965715708*^9, {3.976460503176279*^9, 3.976460582887941*^9}, {
   3.9764606138294687`*^9, 3.976460654192518*^9}, {3.976460694696636*^9, 
   3.976460914913739*^9}, {3.976460963819648*^9, 3.976461035834505*^9}, {
   3.976461069070344*^9, 3.9764612362616243`*^9}, {3.976461286258583*^9, 
   3.9764613875795717`*^9}, {3.976461975140368*^9, 3.976461977046464*^9}, {
   3.976462086969014*^9, 
   3.9764620884340973`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"46a7acf5-1f9b-488d-a652-\
2379334df010"],

Cell["\<\
For historical reasons having to do with the theory of evolution there are \
some oddities in input units : 
RF frequency \[RightArrow] freq is in MHZ
Electron density \[RightArrow] ns is in m^-3, although n0 which appears \
inside the functions is in cm^-3
Magnetic field \[RightArrow] B is in Tesla and converted to Gauss inside the \
functions . 
There are 6 built - in particle species numbered 0 to 5 {electrons, H, D, T, \
He^3, He^4} . Electrons are species zero . Concentrations of the ion are \
specified as fractions of the electron density in the list of length 5 \
\[RightArrow] etaLlist .\
\>", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9764620691873083`*^9, 
  3.976462115182942*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"39be41bc-bc8b-41ae-a0ea-\
5448a80d7388"],

